From: Claude (devcontainer agent)
Date: 2026-04-26
Subject: [I3] .devcontainer/Dockerfile: document trust posture for
         third-party plugin marketplaces

Why this is a separate patch
============================
This devcontainer mounts /workspace/.devcontainer as read-only inside
the container, so an agent running inside cannot edit the Dockerfile
directly. Apply this patch from the host (or any environment with
write access to .devcontainer/), then commit and push.

This patch is a sibling to R5/R6 (curl-bash supply chain + caps) and
to I1/I2/I4/I6/S4 (post_install hardening). Apply all three for full
devcontainer hardening.

What this fixes (review item I3)
================================
The Dockerfile adds three plugin marketplaces unconditionally:

  claude plugin marketplace add anthropics/skills
  claude plugin marketplace add trailofbits/skills
  claude plugin marketplace add trailofbits/skills-curated

`anthropics/skills` is Anthropic-owned and consistent with the trust
already extended to the Claude CLI itself. The two `trailofbits/`
entries are third-party and currently unpinned — Trail of Bits is
reputable, but a compromise of either upstream lands plugin code that
Claude can invoke. Combined with the I4 bypass (when opted in via
SMUDGE_DEVCONTAINER_BYPASS=1) plus the NET_ADMIN/NET_RAW caps and the
R/W workspace mount, plugin compromise has a wide blast radius.

`claude plugin marketplace add` does not expose a SHA-pinning mechanism
that we can wire into the Dockerfile, so the right hardening here is
threefold and depends on actual usage, which only the maintainer can
judge:

  1. If neither trailofbits marketplace is actively used, drop both
     RUN-line entries (one-liner cleanup).
  2. If one of the two covers everything you actually invoke, drop
     the other.
  3. If both stay, document the residual trust event and (when the
     CLI gains pinning) wire it up.

This patch implements (3) — adds a documentation comment so the trust
posture is visible at the call site. It deliberately does NOT drop a
marketplace; the maintainer should evaluate against actual plugin
usage and decide.

How to apply
============
From a shell on the host (NOT inside the devcontainer):

  cd <smudge repo root>
  git apply paad/code-reviews/deferred/I3-dockerfile-marketplaces.patch
  git add .devcontainer/Dockerfile
  git commit -m "docs(devcontainer): document trust posture for third-party plugin marketplaces (I3)"

Then evaluate: do you actively use `trailofbits/skills` and
`trailofbits/skills-curated`? If not, follow up by dropping the
unused entry/entries from the same RUN line.

---
diff --git a/.devcontainer/Dockerfile b/.devcontainer/Dockerfile
--- a/.devcontainer/Dockerfile
+++ b/.devcontainer/Dockerfile
@@ -75,6 +75,22 @@
 ENV PATH="/home/vscode/.local/bin:$PATH"
 
 # Install Claude Code natively with marketplace plugins
+#
+# I3 (review 2026-04-26): the three `claude plugin marketplace add`
+# entries below pull plugin manifests from upstream GitHub repos with
+# no commit/SHA pin. `anthropics/skills` is Anthropic-controlled and
+# consistent with trusting the Claude CLI itself. The two
+# `trailofbits/...` entries are third-party — a compromise of either
+# upstream lands plugin code that Claude can invoke. Combined with
+# bypassPermissions (when opted in via SMUDGE_DEVCONTAINER_BYPASS=1
+# per the I4 deferred patch), NET_ADMIN/NET_RAW caps, and the R/W
+# workspace mount, plugin compromise has a wide blast radius. The CLI
+# does not (yet) expose a SHA-pinning mechanism we can wire in here.
+# Hardening checklist when revisiting:
+#   - Drop any marketplace whose plugins you do not actively invoke
+#   - When the CLI gains pin support, wire it up (one-line discipline)
+#   - Track which plugins you call from each marketplace so future
+#     drops are mechanical
 RUN curl -fsSL https://claude.ai/install.sh | bash && \
   claude plugin marketplace add anthropics/skills && \
   claude plugin marketplace add trailofbits/skills && \
